Identification of prioritized modules

Nguyen Huynh

17 December 2021

Abstract

Prioritized modules were tested for their preservation across different networks (SCZ vs HD). In the case of the GPC-Astrocyte transition network, SCZ and HD were tested against each other, and against the CTR network. This process produced significantly-correlated-to-condition modules, which were also prerserved across diseases. The script then utilized these prioritized modules to extract meaningful biological processes, as well as top-ranked genes.

PART 1: Preserved modules

Here, we showed the identification of preserved and significant modules for the astrocyte networks (HD vs SCZ). The process is similar for the GPC and transition networks.

PART 3: Cluster characterization

After identification of modules that are significantly correlated to and explained by the covariate condition, these modules were pruned to retain only those who were significantly up- or downregulated in both HD and SCZ (same direction). The modules of interest are:
GPC: GPC_SCZ_yellow, GPC_SCZ_purple, GPC_SCZ_lightcyan, GPC_HD_yellow, GPC_HD_salmon, GPC_HD_purple, GPC_HD_lightcyan
Astrocyte: Astrocyte_SCZ_blue, Astrocyte_HD_blue

Investigate the degree of gene overlap for all modules of interest

# A list of genes belonging to modules of interest 
picked_set <- c("GPC_SCZ_yellow", "GPC_SCZ_purple", "GPC_SCZ_lightcyan", "GPC_HD_yellow", "GPC_HD_salmon", "GPC_HD_purple", "GPC_HD_lightcyan", "Astrocyte_SCZ_blue", "Astrocyte_HD_blue")
prior_set <- list()
for (module in picked_set) {
  x <- strsplit(module, "_")[[1]]
  network <- paste0(x[1], "_", x[2])
  module_of_interest <- x[3]
  # Get genes 
  prior_set[[module]] <- names(relabeled_modules[[network]])[relabeled_modules[[network]]==module_of_interest]
}
# Conduct pairwise fisher test for significant overlap of gene content
# 9369 is the number of genes retained after quality cut-off for this study
fisher_res <- compare(m = prior_set, gs = 9369)
fisher_res <- fisher_res[which(fisher_res$Fisher_pVal < 0.1),]
fisher_res$logP <- -log10(fisher_res$Fisher_pVal)
names(fisher_res) <- c("Source", "Target", "pVal", "logPval")

Testing if there is a significant overlap between each TFs targets and each clusters members

tf_overlap <- data.frame(tf= character(), cluster = character(), pval = numeric(), intersection_size = numeric())
for (tf in unique(reg_res$TF)) {
  # Gene overlap test for each TF's target and cluster member
  target <- reg_res$gene[which(reg_res$TF == tf)]
  go <- lapply(node_cluster_all_gn, function(x) newGeneOverlap(x, target, genome.size = 9369))
  go <- lapply(go, testGeneOverlap)
  go.df <- lapply(go, function(x) data.frame(tf=tf, cluster="C", pval=x@pval, intersection_size=length(x@intersection)))
  go.df <- do.call(rbind, go.df)
  go.df$cluster <- row.names(go.df)
  tf_overlap <- rbind(tf_overlap, go.df)
}
# Adjust for multiple comparison
tf_overlap$BH <- p.adjust(tf_overlap$pval, method = "BH")
topTF <- tf_overlap %>% group_by(cluster) %>% top_n(-log10(BH), n = 15)
topTF$logP <- -log10(topTF$BH)
topTF.list <- topTF %>% group_by(cluster) %>% group_split(cluster)
topTF.list <- lapply(topTF.list, as.data.frame)
topTF.list <- lapply(topTF.list, function(x) {z <- x[order(x$logP), ]; z$tf <- factor(z$tf, levels = z$tf); return(z)})
names(topTF.list) <- paste0("C", 1:4)

Visualize

  p <- p + theme(axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "black", size = 8), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8), axis.title.x = element_text(size = 8), title = element_text(size = 8), legend.position = "bottom", legend.box = "vertical", legend.title = element_text(size = 7), legend.text = element_text(size = 7, angle = 30, hjust = 1))

PART 4: Construction of a multilayered network

Edges

Intersecting genes belonging to the aforementioned 9 prioritized modules were extracted. Their correlations within each respective network were imported (Script1 - biweight midcorrelation result) If a pair of genes exhibits more than 1 correlation (for more than 1 network), then the higest weight is picked.

# Take the intersecting genes - This will be genes that are not unique for each cluster 
all <- Reduce(union, prior_set)
uniq <- pullUnique(prior_set)
intersecting_genes <- all[! all %in% uniq]

Here, we demonstrate how to extract correlation weight from the appropriate network. For example: correlation of intersecting genes belonging to module Astrocyte_SCZ_blue from the Astrocyte_SCZ network. This step should be repeated for the other 8 modules in picked_set

bicor.df <- data.frame(Var1=character(), Var2=character(), Freq=numeric(), Module = character())
m <- "Astrocyte_SCZ_blue"
# The biweight midcorrelation matrix 
BIG <- readRDS("./results/Astrocyte_SCZ/bicor.RDS")
# The genes within module Astrocyte_SCZ_blue that are intersecting with other prioritized modules
gid <- prior_set[[m]][which(prior_set[[m]] %in% intersecting_genes)]
cat(paste0("Processing ", m, " with ", length(gid), " genes", "\n"))
# Filter to only keep intersecting genes 
bicor <- BIG$bicor[gid, gid]
pval <- BIG$p[gid,gid]
# wide to long format 
bicor_long <- subset(as.data.frame(as.table(bicor)), match(Var1, colnames(bicor)) > match(Var2, colnames(bicor)))
pval_long  <- subset(as.data.frame(as.table(pval)), match(Var1, colnames(pval)) > match(Var2, colnames(pval)))
bicor_long <- cbind(bicor_long, pval_long$Freq)
# Remove correlation strengths that are not significant 
bicor_long <- bicor_long[which(bicor_long$`pval_long$Freq` < 0.001),]
# Take the top 10% (90th percentile) 
bicor_long <- bicor_long[order(bicor_long$`pval_long$Freq`),]
bicor_long <- bicor_long[which(abs(bicor_long$Freq) >= quantile(abs(bicor_long$Freq), probs = 0.9)),]
bicor_long$Module <- rep(m, nrow(bicor_long))
rm(BIG); gc()

A big data frame of all correlation weights of intersecting genes (compiled from all 9 prioritized modules) is now loaded. This is the edge table.

bicor.df <- readRDS("./results/bicor_all9modules.RDS")
x <- strsplit(bicor.df$Module, "_")
bicor.df$Network <- paste(lapply(x, function(i) i[1]), lapply(x, function(x) x[2]), sep = "_")

Nodes

For each node (gene), the node strength (sum of abs of correlation values) and eigenvector centrality are calculated. This is the node table.

# Make a igraph object, then calculate the eigenvector centrality 
g <- igraph::graph_from_edgelist(as.matrix(bicor.df[,1:2]))
# Calculate eigenvector centrality with supplied weights 
evc <- igraph::eigen_centrality(g, directed = FALSE, scale = TRUE, weights = bicor.df$Freq)
evc <- as.data.frame(evc$vector)

# Collective node strength
var1.strength <- bicor.df %>% group_by(Var1) %>% summarise(FreqAbs=sum(Freq))
var2.strength <- bicor.df %>% group_by(Var2) %>% summarise(FreqAbs=sum(Freq))
strength <- merge(var1.strength, var2.strength, by.x = "Var1", by.y = "Var2", all = TRUE)
strength[is.na(strength)] <- 0
strength$Strength <- apply(strength[,2:3], 1, sum)

# Node table 
node <- merge(strength, evc, by.x = "Var1", by.y = "row.names", all = TRUE)[, c(1,4,5)]
colnames(node) <- c("Node", "Node_Strength", "Eigenvector_Centrality")

Assign cluster to each node

bicor2.df <- bicor.df
colnames(bicor2.df)[1:2] <- c("Var", "Var")
bicor2.df <- rbind(bicor2.df[,c(1,3,5,6)], bicor2.df[,c(2,3,5,6)])
# 
# For each node, if it appears in more than 1 cluster, report all clusters
# By mapping to module name, repeated nodes will be kept because module is unique to cluster
bicor2.df$Cluster <- paste0("C", plyr::mapvalues(bicor2.df$Module, node_cluster$Id, node_cluster$modularity_class))
# Sum all the weights per gene per cluster
bicor2.df <- bicor2.df %>% group_by(Var, Cluster) %>% summarize(Cluster_Node_Strength = sum(Freq))
# In case of repeated nodes, node will be assigned cluster with highest cumulative strength
bicor2.df <- bicor2.df %>% group_by(Var) %>% filter(Cluster_Node_Strength == max(Cluster_Node_Strength))
bicor2.df <- as.data.frame(bicor2.df)

node <- merge(node, bicor2.df, by.x = "Node", by.y = "Var")
node$Node <- as.character(node$Node)
node$geneName <- plyr::mapvalues(node$Node, name2id$ensembl_gene_id, name2id$external_gene_name, warn_missing = FALSE)
node <- node[order(node$Node_Strength, decreasing = TRUE), ]
# Save to ./results for later retrieval 
write.csv(node, "./results/PrioritizedGenes_Multilayered_node.csv", quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE)
write.csv(bicor.df, "./results/PrioritizedGenes_Multilayered_edge.csv", quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE)
